column85: Cont1 Valve Or Device Fail Ind
column168: Description Of Events
DRIVER WAS TRYING TO UNLOAD AND HOSE RUPTURED.

TIE DOWN STRAPS SLIPPED AND DRUM TURNED OVER CAUSING LID TO STRIKE FLOOR AND COME OPEN.  AT TIME OF DISCOVERY ABSORBENT SHEETS WERE PLACED TO STOP LIQUID FROM LEAKING ON GROUND THEN THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP.
column172: Fiber drum, cont1 for solids, cont2 for liquids

column168: CSXT HAZMAT RECEIVED REPORT OF TANK CAR LEAKING FROM HOLE INSIDE OF TANK IN YARD AT CURTIS BAY, MD.  TANK CAR WAS IN STORAGE ON TRACK LEASED BY VISTA CHEMICAL.  A CITIZEN SAW CAR LEAKING AND THE STATE AND THE FIRE DEPT. VISTA CHEMICAL WAS NOTIFIED LOCALLY AND RESPONDED TO MANAGE THE INCIDENT.  THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM A UNDIEL HOLE IN UPPER SIDE OF TANK WELL.  LEAK WAS PLUGGED AND CAR WAS MOVED TO LOCATION WHERE IT WAS TRANSLOADED INTO UTLX 802722.  VISTA CHEMICAL NEUTRALIZED SPILLED PRODUCT WITH SODA TANK.  DAMAGED CAR WAS TAKEN INTO VISTA'S FACILITY AND WAS CLEANED AND PURGED.

column17: HUNT J B SPECIAL COMMODITIES I
column168: DRIVER WAS DOING TIRE CHECK AT A TRUCKSTOP WHEN A STRONG ODOR WAS NOTICED. DRIVER INSPECTED CARGO AND FOUND THAT 4 DRUMS HAD MATERIAL STANDING IN A PUDDLE ON THE TOPS.  THE DRUM WERE OVERFILLED AND EXPANSION CAUSED THE BUNG SEALS TO BE STRESSED AND FAIL.  ABSORBENT WAS USED TO TAKE UP SPILLED MATERIAL AND WAS DISPOSED OF AT RECEIVER.

DUE TO A VERY SLIGHT LEAKAGE (APPROX ONE OUNCE), THERE WAS AN EXTREME ODOR THAT SMELLED LIKE NATURAL GAS.  THIS WAS CALLED IN TO YORK COUNTY CONTROL AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZARDOUS MATERIAL EMERGENCY TEAM WAS DISPATCHED.  THE SUBJECT SHIPMENT WAS INSPECTED AND THE LEAKING PAIL PUT INSIDE A SALVAGE DRUM.

TWENTY PAILS WERE STACKED AND WRAPPED ON A SKID.  WHEN LOADED AT ATL, FORKLIFT BLADE CAME THROUGH BOTTOM OF SKID PUNCTURING BOTTOM OF ONE PAIL. THE MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF AT OKC.  COPIES OF THE MANIFEST AND H/M INCIDENT WILL BE SENT TO ATL FOR REVIEW AND TRAINING.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: DOCKMAN NOTICED CONTENTS ON TRAILER FLOOR WHILE UNLOADING DRUM. INSPECTION OF DRUM REVEALED LOOSE SEAL.
BAGS ON PALLET PROTRUDING OVER PALLET CORNER.  WEIGHT OF BAGS ABOVE CAUSED CORNER OF PALLET TO PUNCTURE BAG.

AFTER TRAILER WAS UNLOADED AT RECEIVER THERE WAS A SMALL WET SPOT IN THE NOSE OF TRAILER FLOOR.  CARGO WAS INSPECTED AND 1 DRUM WAS FOUND THAT HAD A SCRAPED AREA ON THE CHIME SEAM ON THE BOTTOM.  IT APPEARED TO BE AN ABRASION WHICH OCCURED FROM REGULAR HANDLING OF THE DRUM.  SPILL IN NOSE OF TRAILER WAS CLEANED USING ABSORBENT AND FOLLOWED UP WITH A DETERGENT WASH.  ALL WASTE WAS ACCEPTED BY RECEIVER.

ONE THE VAC TRAILER THE CHECK VALVE IN THE TOP TRAILER DID NOT CLOSE AUTOMATICALLY AND IT LET PRODUCT (MINERAL SPIRITS) INTO THE FILTER BREATHER WHICH RESULTED THE PRODUCT TO COME OUT OF THE BREATHER STACK. I THEN SHUT DOWN THE VALVE.  ABSORBANTS WERE THEN PUT DOWN ON THE ASPHALT TO ABSORB THE MINERAL SPIRITS.  THE VAC TRAILER WILL BE TAKEN TO THE SHOP FOR NECESSARY REPAIRS. THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBANTS WHERE PUT IN A 16 GALLON DRUM AND WILL BE SHIPPED OUT.

column168: DRUM WAS LOADED ON THE REAR OF A TRAILER.  DOCK MAN LOADED A SKID OF FREIGHT NEXT TO THE DRUM.  HE PUT THE FORKLIFT IN REVERSE TO BACK UP BUT THE FORKLIFT WENT FORWARD BEFORE ENGAGING THE REVERSE GEAR.  THE BLADE OF THE FORKLIFT PUNCTURED THE DRUM NEAR THE BOTTOM.  DRUM WAS TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR FURTHER HANDLING.  DRUMS SHOULD NOT BE LOADED ON THE REAR OF TRAILERS AND DOCK PERSONNEL SHOULD EXERCISE EXTREME CAUTION WHEN LOADING FREIGHT NEAR DRUMS WITH A FORKLIFT.

column168: THIS PRODUCT WAS PLACED ON A PRE-LOADED TRAILER BY THE SHIPPER, BABSON BROTHERS, AND WAS RECEIVED BY OUR DRIVER ON MAY 14, 1992.  THE LOAD WAS DESTINED FOR STATESVILLE, NC, AND SHORTLY AFTER THE DRIVER LEFT THE SHIPPER, HE STOPPED AT THE CROSSROADS PLAZA TRUCK-STOP NEAR LOWELL, IN FOR DINNER.  AFTER RETURNING TO THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER, HE PERFORMED A VEHICLE INSPECTION PRIOR TO DEPARTURE TO INSURE THAT ALL COMPONENTS ON BOTH UNITS WERE IN GOOD WORKING ORDER.  WHEN THE DRIVER REACHED THE BACK OF THE TRAILER, HE NOTICED A LIQUID SUBSTANCE THAT HAD LEAKED OUT ON TO THE TRAILER BUMPER AND RAILS.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE WERNER ENTERPRISES, INC. SAFETY HOTLINE AND REPORTED THE INCIDENT.  THE SAFETY SUPERVISOR ON STAFF IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE NUMBER AND OUR INSURANCE CARRIER, PROGRESSIVE.  THE LOCAL LAW ENFORCEMENT AND FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE SENT TO THE SCENE WITHIN THIRTY MINUTES TO SECURE THE SCENE.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND SENT A REPRESENTATIVE TO THE SCENE TO SUPERVISE THE INCIDENT.  OUR COMPANY QUICKLY MOBILIZED E.C.C.S, INC., A REPUTABLE SPILL RESPONSE FIRM TO ASSESS THE RELEASE, AND TO CLEAN UP AND DECONTAMINATE THE EQUIPMENT AND SURROUNDING AREA IF NEEDED. THE SPILL RESPONSE FIRM CONFIRMED THAT ONE-15 GALLON PLASTIC DRUM HAD BEEN PUNCTURED AT THE BOTTOM BY A NAIL PROTRUDING FROM A WOODEN SKID ON WHICH IT WAS PLACED FOR SHIPMENT.  THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE PACKAGING HAD LEAKED IN ROUTE, THUS CAUSING NONE TO LEAK ON THE GROUND AT THE LOCATION OF THE TRUCK STOP.  THE SPILL RESPONSE FIRM COMPLETELY DECONTAMINATED THE TRAILER BOTH INSIDE AND OUT AND CONFIRMED THAT THE REMAINING PACKAGINGS WERE SECURED PROPERLY FOR SAFE TRANSPORTATION.  THE TOTAL PRODUCT LOSS WAS ONE-15 GALLON PACKAGE AND NONE OF THE REMAINING PACKAGINGS OR THE TRAILER WERE DAMAGED. AFTER THIS INCIDENT, WE MET WITH THE SHIPPER AND CONFIRMED THAT ALL FUJTURE SHIPMENTS OF THIS TYPE OF PRODUCT AND PACKAGING WILL REQUIRE THAT THEY BE PLACED ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER, SECURED PROPERLY, AND NOT ON WOODEN SKIDS.  SINCE IT WAS NOT A PACKAGING FAILURE, BOTH PARTIES AGREED THAT HIS NEW PROCEDURE SHOULD GREATLY REDUCE ANY RISK OF THE SAME TYPE OF INCIDENT OCCURRING IN THIS FUTURE.

THE LIQUID FLANGE PLATE WAS MISSING 1 OF 4 BOLTS.  ONE OF 3 BOLTS LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT.  THE LOAD WAS REDUCED BY 500 GALLONS, MISSING BOLT REPLACED, ALL BOLTS WERE PROPERLY SECURED AND THE CAR CONTINUED ENROUTE. THE SHIPPER FAILED TO PROPERLY LOAD AND SECURE THE CAR.

THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE CAP HAD BEEN CROSSTHREADED ONTO THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE PIPE.  TIGHTENING THE CAP COULD NOT COMPLETELY STOP THE PRODUCT FORM "BLEEDING" AROUND THE THREADS, WHEN HEAT CAUSED THE PRESSURE TO BUILD UP IN THE TANK.  THE CAP WAS REMOVED, THE THREADS WERE CLEANED UP, TEFLON TAPE WAS APPLIED TO THE THREADS, GENEROUSLY AND THE CAP WAS REAPPLIED STRAIGHT THREADED.  AFTER OFFLOADING, THE CAR WAS SENT IN TO SHOP TO HAVE THE LIQUID EDUCTION FLANGE REPLACED TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN.  THERE WAS LITTLE OR NO GROUND CONTAMINATION, DUE TO THE MINUTE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT BEING RELEASED AND THE DISTANCE OVER WHICH THE PRODUCT HAD LEAKED.

2ND PAILS WERE LOADED ON A PALLET.  ONE OF THE BOARDS ON THE PALLET HAD BROKEN, EXPOSING THE NAILS USED TO SECURE WOOD.  WHEN THE PALLET WAS SET INTO THE TRAILER, THE HEAD OF THE NAILS PUNCTURED PAIL.  SHIPPER SHOULD NOT HAVE USED FRACTURED PALLET.

column168: DRIVER WAS PUMPING GASOLINE FROM ONE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK INTO ANOTHER UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK WHEN HE OVERFILLED IT CAUSING SPILL.

WE WERE DELIVERING A BULK LOAD OF SULFURIC ACID.  THE STORAGE TANK WAS LOCATED ON THE SECOND FLOOR, WHICH REQUIRED THE ACID TO TRAVEL A GREAT DISTANCE THROUGH HOSES BEFORE NETERING THE STORAGE TANK.  AFTER COMPLETING THE TRANSFER, WE PROCEEDED TO CLEAR THE HOSE LINE WITH AIR PRESSURE.  A LEAK DEVELOPED AT A VALVE ON OUR TRAILER DUE TO THE FAILURE OF A GASKET. THE VALVE SHUT-OFF HANDLE WAS MISSING AND REQUIRED A PLIERS TO BE SHUT. CONSEQUENTLY, OUR DRIVER DECIDED IT WOULD BE QUICKER TO STOP THE LEAK BY DISCONNECTING THE AIR LINE FROM THE COMPRESSOR.  THE AIR LINE WAS LAID ON THE GROUND AND THE DRIVER RETURNED TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER TO REPAIR THE GASKET.  WHEN HE RETURNED TO CONNECT THE AIR LINE, HE FOUND ACID BACK FLOWING FROM THE AIR LINE.  APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID LEAKED ON THE GROUND.  OUR DRIVER CONTACTED A PLANT SUPERVISOR AND HE IMMEDIATELY INITIATED CLEAN-UP PROCEDURES.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1150 HOURS, SATURDAY, MAY 13, 1992, EMPLOYEES AT THE CONRAIL STANLEY RAIL YARD IN WALBRIDGE, OH OBSERVED LIQUID PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET OF TANK CAR GLNX-3562 (METHYL ETHYL KETONE).  TANK CAR ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC, SHIPPER, AAR/BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE NOTIFIED. T. DAVIS, DISTRICT INSPECTOR FOR THE AAR/BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES RESPONDED TO THE LOCATION OF THE TANK CAR AND UPON INSPECTION FOUND THAT THE PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM BETWEEN THE TANK CAR SHELL AND THE NOZZLE FLANGE OF A JAMESBURY 4 INCH BALL VALVE.  AN ATTEMPT TO TIGHTEN THE EIGHT FLANGE STUDS BOLTS WAS UNSUCCESSFUL IN STOPPING THE LEAK. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO TRANSFER THE CONTENTS OF THE TANK CAR INTO TANK TRUCKS AND CAR WAS MOVED TO DIESEL #8 TRACK FOR THE TRANSFER OPERATION. TRANSFER BEGAN AT 2000 HOURS, MAY 16, AND WAS COMPLETED AT 0115 HOURS ON MAY 17, 1992.  CAR WAS CLEARED TO DESTINATION.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1830 HOURS, SATURDAY, MAY 21, 1992, MEMBERS OF A CONRAIL TRAIN CREW SMELLED PRODUCT ODOR COMING FROM TANK CAR GATX-93447 (ANHYDROUS AMMONIA).  TANK CAR WAS IN TRAIN WIFP-30 WHICH HAD JUST ARRIVED TO THE CONRAIL RAIL YARD IN FORT WAYNE, IN.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC, SHIPPER, AAR/BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES AND LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT NOTIFIED. RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM OH MATERIALS (REPRESENTING THE SHIPPER - BP CHEMICALS) RESPONDED TO THE LOCATION OF THE TANK CAR AS DID T. DAVIS, DISTRICT INSPECTOR FOR THE AAR/BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES.  INSPECTION OF TANK CAR REVEALED THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM BETWEEN THE MANWAY NOZZLE AND THE PRESSURE PLATE IN VICINITY OF "A" END LIQUID LINE.  ATTEMPT TO STOP LEAK BY TIGHTENING PRESSURE PLATE STUD BOLTS WAS UNSUCCESSFUL. TANK CAR WAS MOVED A SHORT DISTANCE TO LOCATION ON THE MAINTRACK AND ARRANGEMENTS MADE FOR A TRANSFER OF THE PRODUCT TO TANK TRUCKS.  TRANSFER OPERATION BEGAN AT 0700 HOURS, MAY 23, 1992; WAS COMPLETED AT 0415 HOURS MAY 23, 1992.  NO LEAK OF PRODUCT WAS DETECTED AFTER PRODUCT HAD BEEN TRANSFERRED.  TANK CAR WAS STENCILLED IN ACCORDANCE WITH DOT REGULATIONS AND CLEARED FOR SHIPMENT TO THE BP CHEMICAL FACILITY IN LIMA, OH ON MAY 24, 1992.

column168: WHEN LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (FS), INC. TANKER PULLED UP TO THE FINAL UNLOADING PAD, MATERIAL LEAKED OUT OF A BLEED OFF VALVE. APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF MATERIAL FELL ON THE GROUND.  ALL CONTAMINATED DIRT WAS PLACED IN ONE 55-GALLON DRUM.  ONE-HALF OF THE 55-GALLON DRUM WAS FILLED WITH SPILLED MATERIAL.  THIS MATERIAL WILL BE TAKEN TO AN EPA APPROVED DISPOSAL FACILITY.  THE DEFECTIVE VALVE WAS REPLACED AND REPAIRED THAT AFTERNOON.

TRAILER WAS IN PROCESS OF UNLOADING-PALLETIZED LTL CARGO-DOCKMAN UNLOADING TRAILER WITH FORKLIFT WAS TRYING TO PUSH A SKID AROUND WITH THE FORKLIFT BLADES TO ENABLE PENETRATION OF THE SKID WITH THE FORKLIFT.  WHEN THE SKID SLID AROUND IT WAS PUSHED INTO THE SIDE OF THE DRUM THAT WAS DAMAGED CAUSING IT TO BEND INWARDS AT THE BOTTOM CENTER AND THE OTHER FORK ON THE FORKLIFT SLID INTO THE DRUM CAUSING THE CONTENTS TO SPILL OUT OF THE CONTAINER.  APPROX 33 GALLONS OF CONTENTS WERE LOST BEFORE WE WERE ABLE TO GET TO THE DRUM TO CONTAIN THE CONTENTS.  ADDITIONAL TRAINING IN WEEKLY SAFETY MEETINGS WILL HOPEFULLY ASSIST IN OUR CONTINUING EFFORTS OF AWARENESS IN PROPER HANDLING OF FORKLIFTS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS THAT MAY BE ONBOARD AS TO INSURE AVOIDING REOCCURRING INCIDENTS OF THIS NATURE. THIS INCIDENT WOULD SERVE AS PURPOSE EXAMPLE OF THIS TYPE ACCIDENT AND SHOULD ASSIST US IN AWARENESS AND TRAINING. THE SPILLED LIQUID WAS CONTAINED WITH LIQUID SPILL SOCKS AND ABSORBED WITH CLAY MATERIAL AND THE REMAINDER HAD EVAPORATED.  THE CONTAMINATED CLEAN UP MATERIALS WILL BE DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH STATE AND PARISH LAWS SET FORTH BY THE NATURE OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THE RECOVERED MATERIAL WAS TRANSFERRED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND DELIVERED TO THE ORIGINAL CONSIGNEE FOR USE IN MANUFACTURING IT'S DESIGNED INTENT OF FINISHED PRODUCT.

column168: A 55 GALLON DRUM OF A CLEANING COMPOUND, CORROSIVE MATERIAL, WAS NOT BLOCKED AND OVERTURNED IN TRANSIT.  PRODUCT ESCAPED FROM TOP.  DRUM WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACK AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER FOR CREDIT AND INSPECTION.

A PLASTIC DRUM OF A CORROSIVE LIQUID MATERIAL WAS FOUND LEAKING ON ARRIVAL AT PRESTON'S BROOKLYN SERVICE CENTER.  MINIMAL LEAKAGE.  DRUM WAS PATCHED AND FORWARDED TO THE CUSTOMER.  DELIVERED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

DOCKMAN WAS UNLOADING RETURNS FROM PREVIOUS DAY AT 7:15 AM AND SPEARED THE DRUM WITH THE FORKLIFT BLADES.  APPROX 1 GALLON LEAKED FROM THE 55 GALLON DRUM.  WE USED PAPER TOWELS AND SOAKED THE PRODUCT UP AND PLACED THE SOAKED PAPER TOWELS AND THE LEAKING DRUM INTO A RECOVERY DRUM. ACTION TAKEN WAS TO ADVISE DOCKMAN THAT FORKLIFT USAGE ON DRUMS WILL NOT BE TOLERATED.

DRIVER WAS ON AIR CENTER BLVD MAKING A LEFT TURN ON AIR CENTER BLVD IN HOUSTON, TX.  HE WAS CARRYING 2 PALLETS (5 GALLON 36 CANS EACH) OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O.S.  DRIVER HAD BOTH PALLETS TIGHTLY WRAPPED WITH PLASTIC SHRINK WRAP AND HAD TWO (2) STRAPS ACROSS EACH.  SEVERAL CANS TORE THROUGH WRAP AND FELL ONTO THE BED OF THE TRUCK.  WHILE RE-STOCKING CANS DRIVER INHALED FUMES FROM ONE OF THE CANS WHICH THE TOP HAD UNSEALED.  HE RETURNED LOAD TO SHIPPER FOR REPACKING. CORRECTIVE ACTION:  THE TERMINAL MANAGER WAS TOLD TO HAUL THIS PRODUCT WITH SIDES IN THE FUTURE OR TO PLACE AN EMPTY PALLET ONTOP OF CANS BEFORE SECURING THE LOAD.
FREIGHT WAS DROPPED BY DOCKMAN IN UNLOADING.  A MORE SECURE GRIP ON THE FREIGHT WOULD HAVE PREVENTED THE ACCIDENT.  THE CONTENTS EVAPORATED UPON CONTACT WITH THE AIR.

column42: COMPOUNDS, TREE KILLING, LIQUID OR COMPOUNDS, WEED KILLING, LIQUID
column168: DURING TRANSPORTATION, FOR UNKNOWN REASON, THE POLYETHYLENE CONTAINER SIDEWALL SPLIT CAUSING ABOUT 60 GALLONS OF AN AGRICULTURAL HERBICIDE TO SPILL. THE NORTH DAKOTA HIGHWAY PATROL, EDDY COUNTY DEPARTMENT OF EMERGENCY SERVICES, EDDY COUNTY SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT AND NEW ROCKFORD CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE NOTIFIED ABOUT THE SPILL. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP UNDER THE DIRECTION OF MR. EDWARD ALLMERS, EDDY COUNTRY EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATOR. SNYDER INDUSTRIES WAS TOLD ABOUT THE CONTAINER FAILURE.  THEY ASKED FOR A CROSS SECTION OF THE FAILED CONTAINER FOR EVALUATION.

column168: WE WERE IN THE PROCESS OF A ROUTINE TRUCK TO TRUCK TRANSFER OF FOUR STEEL 55 GALLONS DRUMS AT ONE OF OUR SAFETY-KLEEN OIL DEPOTS LOCATED AT THE END OF DUKE DRIVE, SYRACUSE, NY.  WHILE DURING THE TRANSFER ONE OF THE DRUMS WAS TIPPED AND LEAKED APPROX 1/2 PINT OF METHYL ETHYL KETONE AND PAINT BETWEEN THE DRUM LID AND RING.  THE SPILL WAS CONFINED TO THE LIFT GATE OF THE TRUCK.  ALL OF THE MATERIAL WAS REMOVED WITH CLOTH ABSORBENT AND PLACED IN A DRUM. THE FAULTY LID AND SEAL WERE REPLACED AND THE DRUM RESEALED.

DRIVER WAS PUMPING UP GRADE, WHEN TANK RAN DRY.  DRIVER UNCOUPLED HOSE AT PUMP AND WAS ROLLING HOSE TOWARD DROP TANK.  DRIVER SLIPPED IN MUD CAUSING HOSE TO DROP. PICKED UP CTN AND BOTTOM FAILED.  2 GLASS BOTTLES FELL OUT ON CONCRETE FLOOR & BURST.  A FEW DROPS SPLASHED ON SHOES & BOTTOM OF PANTS LEG OF DOCK WORKER.  CHANGED CLOTHES IMMEDIATELY.  LIME WAS SPREAD ON ACID ON FLOOR TO NEUTRALIZE.  INFORMED DOCK WORKERS TO BE EXTREMELY CAREFUL WHEN PICKING UP CARTONS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS & MAKE SURE CARTON IS SECURE.

DURING CLASSIFICATION AND INTERCHANGE OF RAIL CAR, VENT CAP RUPTURED, ALLOWING LIQUID DROPLETS TO SPLASH DOWN SIDE OF CAR WHEN RAILCAR MOVEMENT INVOLVED. CAR WAS ISOLATED, SHIPPER NOTIFIED AND CONTRACTED WITH OUTSIDE SERVICE AGENCY (RESCAR, INC.), REPLACED RUPTURED VENT DISK AND CAR CONTINUED ON TO ORIGINAL WAYBILL DESTINATION.

THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED AT 8:30 PM.  CAUSED BY A CRACKED LINER ON THE TOP DOMELID, APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF SPENT HYDROCHLORIC ACID (10-15% IN WATER CONTAMINATED WITH LEAK AND CADMIUM).  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ON A SMALL STRETCH OF PAVEMENT AND WAS REMOVED USING ABSORBENT.  WE ARE CURRENTLY LOOKING AT OPTIONS FOR TRAILER MODIFICATIONS TO PREVENT RELEASES ALONG WITH TIGHTENED PRE-TRIP CHECKLIST.

column168: UNIT 411/902 WAS NORTH BOUND ON KS. HWY 283 APPROX 8 MILES NORTH OF NORTON KS.  DRIVER DRIFTED ONTO RIGHT SHOULDER.  WHEN THE DRIVER TRIED TO BRING UNIT BACK ONTO HWY EITHER THE RIGHT FRONT TIRE BLEW OUT OR HE TRIED TO BRING UNIT BACK TO FAST AND ROLLED OVER HWY, ON THE LEFT SIDE AND SLIDE INTO THE LEFT DITCH AREA.  THE CARGO TANK EITHER SPLIT OPEN OR WAS RIPPED OPEN FROM AN OBJECT IN THE DITCH.  FROM THE OPENING IN ROAD GRADER WORKING IN THE AREA DAMNED THE DITCH SO NO PRODUCT WOULD RUN AWAY.  DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO LOCAL HOSPITAL.  STANDING PRODUCT WAS PUMPED OUT OF DITCH AREA AND RETAINED IN ANOTHER COMPANY CARGO TANK.
CUSTOMER ORDERED TOO MUCH PRODUCT, WHICH CAUSED THE TANK TO OVERFILL WITH APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  SPILL WAS CLEANED UP WITH SPILL PADS AND CHEM DRY BY THE DRIVER AND THE CUSTOMER.

THE DAFETY-KLEEN DRIVER WAS REMOVING OIL FROM A 16-GALLON DRUM AT SHIPPER'S LOCATION, BY USE OF PIPE AND HOSE, AS PER STANDARD PROCEDURES. THE LINE CLOGGED, SO THE DRIVER TURNED TO UNCLOG THE FILTER AND AT THAT POINT THE WEIGHT OF THE PIPE AND HOSE CAUSED THE DRUM TO TIP OVER.  THIS RESULTED IN A WASTE OIL RELEASE ONTO THE ASPHALT.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY OBTAINED SPILL CLEAN-UP MATERIALS FROM HIS VEHICLE AND CONTAINED THE SPILL.  ONCE THE RELEASE WAS UNDER CONTROL THE DRIVER CONTACTED ME WITH PERTINENT INFORMATION AND THE SPILL WAS THEN REPORTED TO SAFETY-KLEEN'S ENVIRONMENTAL DEPT.  THE DRIVER THEN UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF MARIE HASSE (SHIPER'S ENVIRONMENTALIST), COMPLETED THE REMAINDER OF THE CLEAN-UP.  ALL SPILL MATERIALS WERE PLACED IN DRUMS AND PICKED UP ON MANIFEST NUMBER NJA1441927, BY SAFETY-KLEEN CORP.  ALL MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED, CLEAN UP WAS THOROUGH AND NO WATERWAYS WERE EFFECTED.

THE CAP WAS NOT REPLACED. REPORT BY: JACK WATSON 5/27/92.

column168: TRACTOR TRAILER ENTERED MEDIAN ACCIDENTALLY ON A CURVE.  WHEN DRIVER CORRECTED THE TRACTOR TRAILER WENT SUDDENLY BACK ON CONCRETE ROADWAY AND MOMENTUM OVERTURNED THE UNIT. DUE TO THE ANGLE OF THE ROLLOVER, PRODUCT WAS LOST THROUGH THE RUPTURE DISC WHICH DID NOT FAIL, BUT EXPERIENCED OPENING PRESSURE FROM THE WEIGHT OF THE PRODUCT. PASSING TRUCKS CALLED THE LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE PEOPLE WHO PLUGGED THE RUPTURE DISC OPENING, ATTENDED THE DRIVER, WHO WAS NOT INJURED, DAMMED UP SPILLED PRODUCT IN ROADSIDE DITCH AND NOTIFIED VERTEX OF THE INCIDENT. VERTEX DISPATCHED A TRUCK TO TRANSLOAD THE REMAINING CARGO.  LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM RIGHT THE VEHICLE.  VERTEX SUBSEQUENTLY REMOVED PRODUCT FROM THE DAMMED ARE.  DUE TO HEAVY RAIN, CONTAMINATION WITH DIRT, ETC., AND FIRE DEPARTMENT WASHDOWN, DAMMED PRODUCT HAD CONTENT OF LESS THAN .002% ACTIVE INGREDIENT.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1225 HOURS, WEDNESDAY, MAY 27, 1992, DOT/FRA HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INSPECTOR E. RUDOLPH OBSERVED LIQUID PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET AREA OF TANK CAR GATX-87804 (RESIDUE FUEL OIL).  TANK CAR WAS LOCATED ON #201 TRACK WHEN THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED BY INSPECTOR RUDOLPH WHO WAS CONDUCTING A ROUTINE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RAIL CARS IN THE CONRAIL CONWAY RAIL YARD IN CONWAY, PA.  CAR WAS LEAKING PRODUCT AT THE RATE OF APPROXIMATELY 30 DROPS PER MINUTE. CONRAIL MECHANICAL SUPERVISORY PERSONNEL INSPECTED THE RAIL CAR AND FOUND THAT THE BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE CAP WAS LOOSE AND THAT PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM AROUND THE THREADS OF THE OUTLET NOZZLE.  CAP WAS TOOL TIGHTENED AND PRODUCT LEAK STOPPED.  CAR WAS CLEARED TO DESTINATION AT APPROXIMATELY 1330 HOURS, MAY 27, 1992.

CAR WAS ISOLATED TO A YARD TRACK AND CHEMTREC, THE SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE WERE NOTIFIED. RESPONSE PERSONNEL REPRESENTING THE CONSIGNEE (FLEXEL, INC.) RESPONDED TO THE LOCATION OF THE TANK CAR AND UPON INSPECTION DISCOVERED A RUPTURED FRANGIBLE DISK IN THE CAR'S SAFETY VENT.  THE RUPTURED DISK WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH A NEW DISK.  CAR WAS CLEARED TO DESTINATION AT APPROXIMATELY 1600 HOURS, MAY 20, 1992.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1130 HOURS, FRI., MAY 15, 1992, EMPLOYEES AT THE CONRAIL FLEXI-FLO FACILITY LOCATED WITHIN CONRAIL COLLINWOOD RAIL YARD, CLEVELAND, OH, OBSERVED, LIQUID PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET OF TANK CAR GATX 98614 (HAZARDOUS WASTE, LIQUID, NOS).  TANK CAR HAD JUST BEEN FILLED FROM SEVERAL TANK TRUCKS AND LEAK WAS DISCOVERED.  TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED ON THE B/S TRACK AND A CATCH PAN WAS PLACED UNDER THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK THAT WAS DRIPPING AT THE RATE OF ONE DROP PER SECOND.  THE SHIPPER AND THE AAR/BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES WAS NOTIFIED. ATTEMPTS TO STOP THE LEAK BY CONRAIL MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL, THE SHIPPER AND T.  DAVIS THE RESPONDING INSPECTOR OF THE BUREAU OF THE EXPLOSIVES WERE UNSUCCESSFUL.  ARRANGEMENT WAS MADE TO TRANSFER THE CONTENTS OF THE TANK CAR INTO TANK TRUCKS.  TRANSFER OPERATIONS BEGAN AT APPROXIMATELY 1430 HOURS AND WAS COMPLETED AT APPROXIMATELY 2130 HOURS, MAY 15.  THE SHIPPER (RESEARCH OIL) SUPPLIED THE TANK TRUCKS FOR THE TRANSFER.  TANK CAR WAS CLEARED TO DESTINATION PENDING MARKING OF CAR PER 49 CFR SECTION 174.50.  IT IS SUSPECTED THAT DEFECTIVE GASKET OR "O" RING WAS THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK

THE HEATER COIL FAILURE WAS INSIDE THE TANK CAR AND COULD NOT BE DIRECTLY OBSERVED.  THE CAPS HAD NOT BEEN PROPERLY AFFIXED TO THE OUTLET PIPES OF THE INTERIOR HEATER COILS AS REQUIRED.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR UNIT WHILE TRAVELING EAST ON S/R 150 WE WERE ON A NEWLY REPAVED HIGHWAY THAT THE CONSTRUCTION CREW WRONGLY PLACED THE CENTERLINE STRIPES 3 FT OFF CENTER.  THIS LEFT US ONLY ABOUT 9' LANE.  THE NEW DARK PAVEMENT PLUS THE DARKNESS OF THE NIGHT AND THE DRIVER NOT KNOWING THE STRIPES WERE MISPLACED ALLOWED THE RIGHT FRONT STEERING AXLE WHEEL TO COME OFF THE ROAD ON THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD.  THE DRIVER TRIED TO GET THE WHEEL BACK ON THE ROAD BUT DUE TO A 10" DROP FROM THE ROADWAY WAS HAVING A DIFFICULT TIME GETTING IT BACK ON THE HIGHWAY.  A GUARDRAIL COMING UP RAPIDLY, THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO GET BACK ON THE HIGHWAY BUT IN DOING SO OVER CORRECTED, LOST COMPLETE CONTROL AND THE UNIT ROLLED ON ITS LEFT SIDE.  THE UNIT ROLLED A COMPLETE 360 DEGREE WENT DOWN ABOUT A 35' EMBANKMENT, SEPARATED FROM THE POWER UNIT AND CAME TO REST IN A FIELD.  IN THIS ACCIDENT AT SOME POINT THE OUTER SHELL OF THE TRAILER WAS PUNCTURED CAUSING AN IMMEDIATE AND COMPLETE LOSS OF VACUUM.  THE LOSS OF VACUUM CAUSED THE HELIUM TO VAPORIZE AND VENT THROUGH THE VENT SYSTEM TO THE ATMOSPHERE.  THE HELIUM GAS MIXED WITH THE ATMOSPHERE CAUSED NO ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE.  THE DRIVER RECEIVED RELATIVELY MINOR INJURIES WHICH WAS A MIRACLE DUE TO THE EXTENT OF THE ACCIDENT.  THE PRODUCT DID NOT PLAY ANY ROLE IN THE DRIVERS INJURIES.

ONE OF MY DRIVER/DOCKMAN WAS UNLOADING A TRAILER.  AS SOON AS HE OPENED THE ROLL UP DOOR HE CALLED TO ME TO LOOK AT A SHRINK WRAPPED PALLET OF WHAT APPEARED TO BE 36 CARTONS.  THE PRODUCT (BOTTLES) INSIDE WERE STICKING OUT THRU THR CENTER IN SEVERAL CTNS & LIQUID LEAKED INTO THE CARTONS (CARDBOARD), BUT NOT ONTO THE FLOOR.  IT BURNED THE EYES SO HE MOVED IT OUTSIDE.  NOTHING LEAKED OUT, AS IT ALL ABSORBED INTO THE OUTER CARTON MATERIAL.  ABOUT 6 TO 8 BOTTLES, PLASTIC, 1 GALLON APPEAR TO HAVE COLLAPSED ABOUT MID POINT ALLOWING LEAKS TO SPRING IN THEIR SIDES.  MOST THE LIQUID LEAKED OUT & SOAKED UP.  I PULLED OUT 151 GOOD BOTTLES & PUT 6 OR 8 PARTIAL BOTTLES & ALL THE CONTAMINATED CARDBOARD OUTER CARTONS INTO A RECOVERY DRUM (55 GALLON).  EVERYTHING WAS CONTAINED & NOTHING SPILLED. DAMAGED PORTIONS FORWARDED TO CFMF SACRAMENTO IN ACCORDANCE WITH 40 CFR 173.5 AND 177.854 TO BE PICKED UP BY DISPOSAL CO. 6-22-92.

IT APPEARS THAT WHILE IN TRANSIT THE LIDS ON THE PLASTIC BOTTLES CAME LOOSE.  AS THEY CAME LOOSE, ACID SPILLED OUT OF THE BOTTLES, ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM (RIEDELL ENVIRONMENTAL) WAS CALLED IN TO CLEAN UP THE ACID.  I FEEL THAT THE SHIPPER NEEDS A BETTER METHOD TO PREVENT SPILLAGE OF THE PRODUCT.

column168: DRIVER MOMENTARILY DISTRACTED BY FALLING OBJECT IN CAB WHILE NEGOTIATING CURVED OFF-RAMP SHOULDER.  WHEN TRUCK'S LEFT WHEELS WERE BROUGHT BACK ONTO THE PAVEMENT, THE TRAILER'S LEFT WHEELS REFUSED TO FOLLOW DUE TO THE SEVERE SLOPING AND SOFT DIRT OF THE SHOULDER WHICH CAUSED THE TRAILER WITH BIN TO DISENGAGE FROM TRUCK AND TIP OVER.  THERE WAS ONLY SIX INCHES OF PAVEMENT TO THE LEFT OF THE 4" BERM AFTER WHICH THE ROADWAY SHOULDER SLOPED SEVERLY DOWNHILL AND CONSISTED OF EXTERMELY SOFT DIRT.  SPEED NOT AN APPARENT FACTOR.  SPILL WAS COMPLETELY OFF OF THE ROADWAY ONTO SOFT DIRT.  THE OFF RAMP WAS NOT AFFECTED AND TRAFFIC REMAINED NORMAL.  RURAL AREA, PUBLIC NOT AFFECTED.  CALTRANS AND C.H.P. RESPONDED AS WELL AS OUR CLEANUP CREW. BIN WAS UP-RIGHTED, INSPECTED AND FOUND ONLY VERY MINOR DAMAGE AND STILL LEAKPROOF DUE TO VERY SOFT DIRT ON WHICH IT LANDED.  THE SPILL WAS RELOADED INTO SAME BIN, TARPED AND TRANSPORTED TO ORIGINAL DESTINATION. NO DAMAGE TO ENVIRONMENT.  TOTAL OF 3 HOURS FROM TIME OF ACCIDENT TO CLEARING THE SCENE. column168: SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF A CAPSULE OF SOLID SALT IODINE 131 ENCLOSED IN A SMALL PLASTIC VIAL.  THE VIAL WAS KEPT INSIDE A 12 LB LEAD PIG.  THE COVER FOR THE PIG WAS TAPED ONTO THE PIG.  THERE WAS NO OTHER SECURING MEANS. THE PIG WAS THEN PLACED INSIDE A 7A FIBERBOARD BOX.  THE BOX HAD A CARDBORAD SPACER INSIDE TO PREVENT HORIZONTAL SHIFT OF THE PIG.  THERE WAS NO SPACER TO PREVENT VERTICAL SHIFT.  THE PIG DROPPED OUT THROUGH THE BOTTOM SEAL OF THE BOX WHERE THE FLAPS CLOSE.  THE PACKAGE DID NOT HAVE SUFFICIENT STRENGTH TO HOLD THE PIG INSIDE UNDER ANY MOMENTUM.  IN ADDITION, THE LID FOR THE PIG DID NOT HAVE ANY SECURITY DEVICE OTHER THAN TAPE.  NO FRICTION CLOSE, CLIP, SCREW ON OR SCREW DOWN SECURITY AT ALL. AS THE PIG IS MEANT TO PROVIDE ADEQUATE SHIELDING OF THE RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL I FEEL THIS IS THE PROBLEM WITH THIS PACKAGE.  THIS SHIPMENT COST FEDERAL EXPRESS CONSIDERABLE TIME AND EXPENSE IN CLEAN-UP PROCESS.

OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE PICKERING PLANT TO DELIVER A LOAD APPROXIMATELY 4,000 GALLONS OF ALUMINUM SULFATE.  HE WAS DIRECTED WHERE TO HOOK UP HIS HOSE AND TO START UNLOADING.  THE STORAGE TANK IS LOCATED INSIDE A BUILDING AND THE HOSE HOOK-UP IS LOCATED OUTSIDE.  THE STORAGE TANK CANNOT BE SEEN BY THE DRIVER WHO REMAINED WITH HIS VEHICLE.  PLANT PERSONNEL ARE RESPONSIBLE FOR MONITORING THEIR TANK LEVEL.  THE TANK DID NO HAVE ENOUGH ROOM TO HOLD THE ENTIRE LOAD.  APPROX., 1,000 GALLONS OVERFLOWED FROM THE STORAGE TANK INTO A CONTAINMENT AREA AND THEN PUMPED IN A SLUDGE POND. THE SLUDGE POND IS WHERE THE ALUMINUM SULFATE WOULD NORMALLY BE USED.  NO MATERIAL WAS RELEASED TO THE ENVIRONMENT.

A LOAD OF SPECIFICATION OIL WAS BEING DELIVERED AND OFF-LOADED FROM AN 8300 GALLON TRANSPORTER INTO A RECEIVING TANK WHEN THE TRANSFER HOSE FAILED ALLOWING 40-50 GALLONS OF THE ABOVE MENTIONED FUEL OIL TO BE RELEASED.  EMPLOYEES OF P.J. KEATING IMMEDIATELY COVERED THE AFFECTED AREA WITH STONE DUST WHICH ACTED AS AN EFFECTIVE ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED HIS DISPATCHER WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED BOTH THE MASSACHUSETTS DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT.  A CLEAN-UP CREW WAS IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF KINGSTON'S SHREWSBURY MA OFFICE AND ARRIVED ON SITE ONE HOUR FROM THE TIME OF THE INITIAL CONTACT. PLEASE NOTE THAT ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED AT ALL TIMES AND PRESENTED NO DANGER OF MIGRATING TO ANY WATER SOURCE.  THE CLEAN-UP CREW CONTAINERIZED THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL INTO 5 55 GALLON DRUMS AND COMPLETED THE CLEAN-UP OF THE AREA.  THE DRUMS THAT WERE GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE WERE SHIPPED OFF SITE ON JUNE 3, 1992 TO A FULLY LICENSED TRANSFER, STORAGE AND DISPOSAL FACILITY. IN ORDER TO PREVENT A REOCCURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, ALL DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO COMPLETE A THOROUGH INSPECTION OF ALL EQUIPMENT PRIOR TO INITIATING ANY OPERATION.  FURTHERMORE, THE HOSES ON ALL UNITS THAT ROUTINELY CONDUCT THIS TYPE OF DELIVERY HAVE BEEN REPLACED.

INCIDENT OCCURRED WHEN THIS SMALL GAS TRAILER WAS BEING FILLED.  ONE EMPLOYEE WENT OUTSIDE TO THE TRAILER FROM THE FILLING ROOM TO TIGHTEN THE NUT ON THE HIGH PRESSURE HOSE ON THE TRAILER CONNECTION.  ANOTHER EMPLOYEE CAME OUT AND STOOD ON THE WRENCH HANDLE TO HELP TIGHTEN THE NUT,  BOTH EMPLOYEES FAILED TO TURN OFF THE TRAILER CONNECTION.  THE NUT, THEN CAME LOOSE AND THE HIGH PRESSURE NITROGEN IN THE TRAILER ESCAPED, KNOCKING BOTH INDIVIDUALS TO THE GROUND.  BOTH EMPLOYEES WERE TREATED AT HARTFORD HOSPIRTAL AND DISCHARGED WITH BRUISES.  ONE WAS SUBSEQUENTLY HOSPITALIZED FOR A LEG INJURY 3 DAYS LATER.  ACTION TO RPEVENT FUTURE OCCURRANCE: EMPLOYEES HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED THAT THEY MUST SHUT OFF ALL LINES AND CONNECTIONS BEFORE ATTEMPTING TO TIGHTEN OR LOOSEN A HIGH PRESSURE NUT.

column168: OUR DRIVER LOADED AT SOUTHERN FACILITIED TERMINAL AT MONTGOMERY, AL AND FINISHED THIS TASK AT 10:14 A.M. BY THE TIME HE GOT HIS DRIVERS LOG UPDATED WITH THE NECESSARY ENTRIES AND HIS TRIP SHEET FILLED OUT, HE PROCEEDED ENROUTE TO CIRCLE A FOOD STORE AT RUTLEDGE, AL., ABOUT AN HOUR'S DRIVE AWAY.  TRAVELING SOUTH ON US #31 HE CAME OVER A HILL AND A BLUE TOYOTA CAR WAS TOPPED IN THE MIDDLE OF THE ROAD, MAKING A LEFT TURN.  THE DRIVER HAD A CHOICE OF HITTING THE CAR OR HEADING FOR THE SHOULDER TO AVOID A COLLISION.  ONCE HE HIT THE SHOULDER THE TRAILER AND TRACTOR ROLLED ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE, FINALLY COMING TO REST ON ITS LEFT SIDE.  THE DRIVER WAS CONSCIENTIOUS AND STARTED BEEING HIS HORN UNTIL THE MAN ACROSS THE STREET CAME OVER AND HELPED HIM OUT OF THE VEHICLE.  HE CUT HIS ARM IN THE PROCESS AND WAS TREATED BY A PARAMEDIC AT THE SCENE AND RELEASED,  THE CHAIN OF EVENTS THAT FOLLOWED WAS NOTIFICATION VIA 911 TO THE HIGHWAY PATROL, FIRE DEPT., ETC.  THE DRIVER HAD THE TROOPERS NOTIFY OUR OFFICE IN ANDALUSIA AND THAT STARTED THE BALL ROLLING ON GETTING AN EMPTY TANKER ON SIGHT, A CLEAN-UP CREW ENROUTE, CONTACTING THE ALA. DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, ROUNDING UP THE ABSORBENT, ETC.  IN LESS THAN FOUR HOURS THE TRUCK CONTENTS WERE PUMPED INTO AN EMPTY TANKER AND THE OVERT URNED VEHICLE UPRIGHTED AND TOWED TO A REPAIR.

INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE MANWAY COVER PLATE SWING BOLTS WERE LESS THAT WRENCH TIGHT.  TWO OF THE SIX NUTS WERE LOOSE ENOUGH TO ALLOW THE SWING BOLTS TO BE DISENGAGED.  IN TACT SEALS ON COVER PLATE WERE CSX I 574888 AND CSX I 574890. SWING BOLTS WERE SECURED AND CAR WAS RELEASED FOR CONTINUED TRANSPORTATION.  JOE BARBER OF CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column42: PHOSPHORUS WHITE OR YELLOW, IN WATER
column168: SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SA/HM) C.D. HUGGINS WAS NOTIFIED BY WESTERN CORRIDOR MANAGER, D. FOLMER THAT TANK CAR MONX 13015 WAS LEAKING PHOSPHORUS AND WAS ON FIRE NEAR MONTPELIER, IDAHO.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, CHEMTREC AND MONSANTO PERT WERE ALL NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT. SA/HM HUGGINS RESPONDED AND ASSISTED THE MONTPELIER FIRE DEPARTMENT AND MEMBERS OF THE MONSANTO PERT TEAM TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE.  THE CAR WAS STABILIZED AND THE UNLOADING VALVE WAS DETERMINED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK. THE VALVE WAS REMOVED AND REPAIRED AND PLACED BACK ON THE TANK CAR.  CAR WAS TO BE RETURNED TO MONSANTO AT SODA SPRINGS FOR UNLOADING, CLEANING AND COMPLETE INSPECTION/REPAIR.

RAIL CAR GATX 23906 CONTAINING 93% SULFURIC ACID WAS BEING UNLOADED TO STORAGE TANK TS-27.  THE RAIL CAR WAS PADDED WITH AIR AND WAS BEING PUMPED OFF.  THE CAR IS UNLOADED FROM THE TOP.  WHEN THE CAR HAD APPROXIMATELY 500 GALLONS REMAINING SUCTION WAS LOST.  THE PUMP CONTINUED TO RUN GENERATING ENOUGH HEAT TO MELT THE INSIDE LINING OF THE HOSE AT THE PUMP INTAKE.  WHEN SUCTION WAS REGAINED THE FORCE OF THE LIQUID ON THE DAMAGED HOSE CAUSED THE HOSE TO BLOW OFF THE SHANK.  THE AIR PRESSURE IN THE CAR BLEW OUT THE REMAINDER OF THE ACID ONTO THE GROUND AT THE RAIL SIDING. DELTA EMPLOYEES WERE ABLE TO CLOSE THE VALVE ON THE CAR AND BEGAN NEUTRALIZING THE ACID WITH SODA ASH. THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS CALLED.  REPORT NUMBER 116655.  THE EMERGENCY SPILL NIGHT NUMBER 974-3551 WAS CALLED AND THE SPILL REPORTED TO POLICE COMMUNICATION OFFICER MELTON. THE U.S.C.G. MARINE SAFETY OFFICE RESPONDED AS DID MDE EMERGENCY RESPONSE VEHICLE WITH MR. R.J. SWANN. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED, NEUTRALILZED AND CLEANED UP BY DELTA CHEMICAL CORPORATION EMPLOYEES.  THE MATERIAL RESULTING FROM THE CLEANUP WILL BE DISPOSED OF BY EASTERN CHEMICAL WASTE SYSTEMS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITHIN A 10 FOOT BY 60 FOOT AREA ON DELTA CHEMICAL CORPORATION PROPERTY.

column42: HAZARDOUS WASTE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column168: SPILL HAPPENED AT THE INTERSECTION OF HIGH SCHOOL ROAD AND US 40.  THE TRUCK WAS WEST BOUND.  THE SPILL COVERED A 5 FT. BY 8 FT. AREA ON THE ROAD WAY. ALBERT BERTON WITH HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL CALLED TERRA FIRST, INC. AT 7:20 AM ON 5/15/92 AND INFORMED THE DISPATCHER CHARLES ROBERTSON THAT THE SPILL HAD BEEN CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP.  SPILL WAS APPROXIMATELY ONE (1) MILE FROM THE GATE GOIND TO THE HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL DISPOSAL FACILITY. ALBERT BERTON HAD CONTACTED CARL SAVINON WITH UNITED TECHNOLOGY TO ADVISE HIM OF THE SPILL.  CARL STATED THAT THE LOAD LOOKED DRY WHEN THE BOX WAS LOADED, BUT THAT THEY HAD A PROBLEM WITH THEIR SYSTEM AND THEY KNEW THE LOAD WAS WET.  THE LIQUID WAS AT THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX AND AS THE LOAD VIBRATED DOWN THE ROAD THE LIQUID WORKED TO THE TOP OF THE BOX. THEREFORE, SPILLING OUR WHEN THE DRIVER STOPPED OR STARTED OFF.  ALBERT BERTON WITH HERITAGE STATED THAT IN HIS OPINION THE DRIVER (ROBERT ALLEN) WAS AT NO FAULT.
column172: Highway hopper trailer for solid materials only

column168: AT 2030 HOURS ON 5/29/92, MARTY DEVOLDER CALLED ME ON THE RADIO TO ADVISE THAT HE HAD A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPILL ON PRO 109-120690, 67 LBS. CHLOROFORM, AN ORM-A.  RAY PETTAVINO, DOCKMAN, WAS LOADING FREIGHT INTO TRAILER 17-7209 FOR MEMPHIS, TN WHEN HE KNOCKED THIS 67 LB CARTON OFF A SKID TO THE FLOOR, WHERE A 4 LITER BOTTLE BROKE AND BEGAN LEAKING.  MARTY CLOSED THE TRAILER DOOR AND MOVED THE TRAILER TO WEST END, DOOR 206, WHERE NO ONE WAS WORKING.  CHEMTREC NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY.  AFTER SPEAKING TO CHEMTREC, I PHONED HERITAGE REMEDIATION TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL, BASED ON ADVISE FROM CHEMTREC THAT NO ONE SHOULD ATTEMPT TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL WITHOUT POSITIVE BREATHING APPARATUS.  HERITAGE ARRIVED AT APPROX. 2330 HOURS.  THEY DECONTAMINATED THE TRAILER AND CLEANED UP BROKEN GLASS AND CARDBOARD.  THEY PACKED 3 REMAINING 4-LITER BOTTLES IN A GOOD CONTAINER. THE SHIPMENT HAS BEEN FORWARDED TO DESTINATION IN A NEW CONTAINER.  TWO SMALL CONTAINERS OF DEBRIS WERE GENERATED AND WILL BE PICKED UP BY HERITAGE AT A FUTURE DATE FOR PROPOSAL.  HERITAGE PROVIDED ME WITH AN MSDS SHEET.  A COPY OF MSDS SHEET WILL BE PLACED IN MD. DEVOLDER'S FILE AND R. PETTAVINO'S FILE.  MO MARKS WERE OBTAINED FROM THE PACKAGING.  A REPRESENTATIVE FROM BAXTER HEALTHCARE CALLED ME, BUT OFFERED LITTLE HELP. HE DID TELL ME NOT TO ALLOW ANYONE TO GO NEAR THE SPILL WITHOUT POSITIVE BREATHING APPARATUS. TWO CONTAINERS OF DEBRIS ARE SITTING ON OUR DOCK AT THE WEST END, AND HAVE BEEN LABELED WITH ALL NECESSARY INFORMATION.  MR. PETTAVINO HAS BEEN INFORMED THAT HE WILL RECEIVE A WARNING LETTER FOR DAMAGING FREIGHT.

20' CONTAINER EMCU 286768 FOUND DRIPPING FROM BOTTOM WHILE ON ASPHALT IN CSXT'S HULSEY YARD, ATLANTA, GA LEAKING MATERIAL COLLECTED WITH SAND, THEN SECURED WITH PLASTIC SHEETING.  INSPECTION OF CONTENTS REVEALED IMPROPER LOADING, WITH DRUMS LOADED INDIVIDUALLY, STACKED 2 X HIGH, WITH 2 DRUMS LOADED ON SIDES ON TOP. ONE (1) OF THESE DRUMS LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 35 GALLONS FROM BUNG.  PRIVATE CONTRACTOR REMOVED DRUMS, CLEANED UP SPILLAGE ON DRUMS, IN CONTAINER, AND ONGROUND.  LOAD REPLACED ON SEPARATE 40' BOX TRAILER, PLACARDED, AND ISSUED NEW SHIPPING DOCUMENT BY CONSIGNEE. CONTACTS ASHLAND CHEMICAL - DAN BROWN 404/448-7010; EVERGREEN ART PRUITT 4049532626.

ROUTINE INSPECTION BY BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES INSPECTOR JARVIS FOUND RUPTURE DISC BLOWN AND MINIMAL RESIDUE OF PRODUCT ON TOP OF CAR.  CAR WAS LOADED SUCH THAT LIQUID LEVEL WAS UP TO TOP OF TANK.  SUFFICIENT OUTAGE OBTAINED BY OFF LOADING CAR BEFORE RETURNING TO TRANSPORTATION.  INSPECTOR REPLACED RUPTURE DISC AND WILL HANDLE ISSUES WITH SHIPPER.

CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC, SHIPPER, AAR/BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES AND LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE NOTIFIED. RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM THE CONSIGNEE (ASHLAND) RESPONDED TO THE LOCATION OF THE TANK CAR BUT WERE UNABLE TO FIND ANY SOURCE OF LEAK OR PRODUCT ODOR WHEN THEY INSPECTED THE CAR.  AAR/BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES SENIOR INSPECTOR T. MANNAS ARRIVED TO THE LOCATION OF THE CAR AT 1317 HOURS AND UPON INSPECTION FOUND EVIDENCE OF PRODUCT AT THE AREA AROUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET ROD WHICH WAS TIGHTENED 3/4 TURN BY MR. MANNAS.  THE PACKING GLAND NUT FOR THE OPERATING ROD WAS ALSO FOUND LOOSE AND TIGHTENED ONE FULL TURN.  NO LEAK OR ODOR COULD BE DETECTED UPON REPAIR BY MR. DRIVER BILL NOBLES WAS EN ROUTE TO MOUNTAIN CITY, TN TO DELIVER 25-55 GALLON DRUMS OF 25% CAUSTIC.  WHILE EN ROUTE THE DRIVER STOPPED TO USE THE REST FACILITIES IN MOORESVILLE, N.C. ON I-77.  UPON LEAVING THE REST FACILITY THE DRIVER CHECKED HIS LOAD AND FOUND A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID ON THE SIDE OF A DRUM.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION ONE DRUM WAS FOUND TO HAVE A SMALL PINHOLE APPROXIMATELY 2" FROM THE TOP OF THE DRUM.  THE MATERIAL WAS FILLED BELOW THAT LEVEL BUT, WHEN THE TRUCK WAS PUT INTO AN OVERPACK DRUM BY JONES CHEMICALS PERSONNEL AT THE SCENE.  ALL APPROPRIATE AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.  MATERIAL ON THE TRAILER WAS CLEANED UP AND BROUGHT BACK TO PLANT.  MATERIAL WAS WIPED UP WITH RAGS AND THE RAGS WERE PLACED IN THE OVERPACKS WITH THE DRUM.

column168: ON MAY 22, 1992 AROUND 10:00AM OUR DRIVER, MR. MARVIN BARRITT, WAS WAITING TO DUMP HIS LOAD AT THE CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT LANDFILL, STAR ROUTE, ARLINGTON, OR 97812.  THERE WAS A SHORT IN THE PIGTAIL WHICH OPENED THE TAILGATE PREMATURELY RELEASING ABOUT (1) ONE YARD OF MATERIAL ON THE ROADWAY. CHEMICAL WASTE SCOOPEED UP THE MATERIAL AND DUMPED IT RIGHT FROM THE SCRAPER ONTO THE DUMP SITE WHICH WAS ABOUT 1/4 MILE AWAY FROM THE SPILL. THE MATERIAL WAS (RQ HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID, NOS, ORM-E, NA9189 (K008) SPENT ELECTROLYTIC POT LINING.  MANIFEST #01595. JACK GRAY TRANSPORT, INC NOTIFIED NATIONAL RESPONSE, REPORT #118846 AND MAILED COPIES TO THE WRITTEN REPORT TO OREGON DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENT QUALITY, ALUMINUM CO OF AMERICA, 5509 LOWER RIVER ROAD, VANCOUVER, WA 98660 (THE SHIPPER) AND CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT LANDFILL.

AFTER OFF LOADING 10 BAGS, NOTICED LIQUID ON THE BIN FLOOR WHEN PICKING UP A SMALL CLOTH DUFFLE BAG.  THE BAG FELL APART ON THE LEFT SIDE.  HE OPENED THE BAG AND FOUND 2 PAPER BAGS, OPENED PAPER BAGS AND FOUND A CAR BATTERY.  UNDER THE BAG WAS A PUDDLE OF LIQUID (CLEAR AND RED).  LIQUID WAS THEN CLEANED UP.

column168: SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SA/HM) C.D. HUGGINS WAS NOTIFIED BY CPL. JACK ANDERSON OF THE IDAHO STATE POLICE TO REPORT A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL LEAK FROM TRAILER BMDZ 630212.  THE TRAILER WAS BEING PULLED BY UNION PACIFIC MOTOR FREIGHT AND WAS LOCATED AT INKOM PORT OF ENTRY WHERE IT WAS STOPPED FOR INSPECTIONS/WEIGHING.  THE TRAILER WAS IMPROPERLY PLACARDED AND OPENED FOR INSPECTION.  WHEN DOORS WERE OPENED PRODUCT SPILLED OUT OF THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  SSA/HM HUGGINS RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT AT LEAST THREE, 30 GALLON DRUMS WERE OPEN AND LEAKING PRODUCT.  CPL. ANDERSON ALLOWED THE TRACTOR TRAILER TO RETURN TO POCATELLO, IDAHO RAMP FOR PROPER TRANSFER OF LOAD. SA/HM HUGGINS CONTACTED SCOTT SPRAGUE OF KERR MCGEE.  MR. SPRAGUE AND WORK CREW RESPONDED TO OFFLOAD AND REPAIR DAMAGE TO CONTAINERS.  14 METAL DRUMS WERE FOUND TO BE DAMAGED OR LEAKING.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED AND DAMAGED DRUMS WERE REPAIRED.  HALF OF THE LOAD WAS LOADED INTO TRAILER USAZ 631570 AND BOTH TRAILERS WERE INSPECTED BY CPL. ANDERSON AND BRUCE MARRIOT (FRA).  CORRECT PLACARDS WERE APPLIED TO THE TRAILER.

column168: SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SA/HM) R.L. CERDA WAS NOTIFIED OF A LEAKING TRAILER BMDZ 630949 AT PORT LAREDO, TX.  TRAILER WAS ISOLATED AND SA/HM CERDA RESPONDED.  SA/HM CERDA'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH TWELVE TOTE BINS.  THREE OF THE TWELVE BINS WERE FOUND LEAKING PRODUCT.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE INNER LINER AND THE OUTER SHELL HAD RUBBED AGAINST ONE ANOTHER AND HAD CAUSED THE LINER TO FAIL.  BASF EMERGENCY, JOSEPH STEFANON WAS NOTIFIED AND MADE ARRAMGEMENTS FOR EMTECH TO RESPOND AND TRANSFER, RELOAD AND DECONTAMINATE TRAILER. EMTECH RESPONDED, TRANSFERRED LOAD AND DECONTAMINATED TRAILER.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: TANK CAR GATX 56498 WAS NOTED LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) D.C. COOPER RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE #3 MANWAY COVER PLATE BOLT WAS FINGER TIGHT.  THE MANWAY GASKET WAS INSEPCTED AND FOUND TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION.  ALL MANWAY COVER PLATE BOLTS WERE PROPERLY SECURED. CAR WAS MOVED SEVERAL TIMES TO ENSURE PROPER CONTAINMENT.  CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT. CHEMTREC, CALIFORNIA OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES AND THE COUNTY OF SAN BERNARDINO ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH SERVICES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: WAS NOTIFIED BY ASST SUPT B. WALLACE AT APPROX 3:00 PM, 5-29-92 THAT TANK CAR RUSX 590 WAS LEAKING.  CAR WAS LOCATED AT OUR PENN CITY YARD AND ON ARRIVAL, FOUND CAR LEAKING FROM (BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE) WHERE OUTLET VALVE IS BOLTED INTO TANK CAR.  GATX PERSONNEL WERE ON SITE AND COULD NOT DO FIELD REPAIRS.  MR. JAMES L. DAVIS, FIELD OPERATIONS SUPERVISOR FOR MERICHEM COMPANY WAS PRESENT AND ALSO HIS HAZ-MAT REPRESENTATIVE, MR. KINK.  AT THIS TIME, WE PLACED A BUCKET UNDER NORTH BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. AT APPROX, 4:30 PM A SPECIAL MOVE WAS MADE TO SPOT CAR INTO MERICHEM FOR THE PURPOSE OF UNLOADING CAR.  RESUMED NORMAL OPERATIONS AT 5:15 PM.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND WAS TO BE PURGED AND SENT HOME SHOP FOR REPAIRS, AS PER MERICHEM CO.

column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) A.M. ROQUET WAS NOTIFIED THAT TANK CAR GATX 55117 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET. SSA/HM ROQUET RESPONDED AND MCALESTER FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON THE SCENE. SSA/HM ROQUET'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE PACKING MATERIAL IN THE PACKING GLAND OF THE TOP OEPRATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS WORN AND INEFFECTIVE.  THEP ACKING GLAND WAS REPACKED WITH TEFLON ROPE GASKET AND THE CAR WAS SECURED FOR MOVEMENT.  SEAL UP B203001 WAS APPLIED TO THE VALVE.  TOM FLORES OF CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: WHILE CONDUCTING TANK CAR INSPECTIONS, SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SA/HM) F.H. LERCH NOTED TGAX 131347 HAD PRODUCT ON THE TOP AND SIDES OF THE CAR.  SA/HM LERCH'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE FRANGIBLE DISC INSIDE THE SAFETY VENT HOUSING HAD RUPTURED.  SA/HM LERCH REPLACED THE FAILED FDI, 100 PSI, DISC WITH A NEW CDC, 100 PSI, DISC WHICH SECURED CAR FOR MOVEMENT.  TOM FLORES OF CHEMTREC, BARB NICHOLS OF NEBRASKA STATE PATROL AND SCOTT MCINTYRE OF NEBRASKA STATE ENVIRONMENTAL WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EMERGENCY RESPONSE, R.M. STINE WAS NOTIFIED BY YARDMASTER JACK FURLONG THAT PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM A TOP FITTING ON CAR NATX 29919.  CAR WAS LOCATED ON TRACK 203, NEFF YARD.  MANAGER STINE RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT LIQUID WAS LEAKING FROM BEANEATH THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVERING THE LIQUID LINE, VACUUM RELIEF VALVE AND AIR INLET.  IN TACT SEAL UP C265253 WAS REMOVED AND LIQUID WAS SPRAYING FROM THE BASE OF THE VALVE AT THE THREADED CONNECTION.  THE VALVE COULD BE REMOVED BY HAND.  THE HEAT OF THE DAY HAD CREATED A SLIGHT INTERNAL PRESSURE ALLOWING PRODUCT TO PERCOLATE UP THE LIQUID LINE.  PRESSURE WAS RELIEVED AND LIQUID VALVE WAS REMOVED, THREADS WERE CLEANED AND TEFLON TAPE WAS APPLIED WHICH SECURED LEAK.  SEAL UP X 140930 WAS APPLIED AND CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.  JIM COOPER OF CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED.

WHILE CONDUCTING TANK CAR INSPECTIONS SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SA/HM) C.D. WOMACK NOTED A STRONG AMMONIA SMELL CLOSE TO CAR GATX 97473. INSPECTION DETERMINED A SMALL VAPOR LEAK FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. SA/HM WOMACK AND BOBBY LAMBRIGHT (ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY SPECIALIST) ATTEMPTED TO SECURE LEAK BUT WAS UNSUCCESSFUL.  SA/HM WOMACK CONFERRED WITH LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, SHIPPER, TRAIN MANAGEMENT AND AGENT LAMBRIGHT AND DECISION WAS MADE TO REPAIR CAR IN THE YARD.  FARMLAND INDUSTRIES REPRESENTATIVES, PENNY ZELL, JEWELL JACKSON AND MAINTENANCE CREW RESPONDED AND REPLACED THE DEFECTIVE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT.

FORDEMWALT REPLACED FAILED DISC WITH NEW LIKE DISC WHICH SECURED THE CAR FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT.  BILL CASON OF CHEMTREC, STAN ANDERSON OF KENNECOTT UTAH COPPER AND BRUCE CARRIER OF GREAT WESTERN CHEMICAL WERE ALL NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

THE PACKAGE WAS CAUGHT IN THE SORT AISLE SIDE I AND BROUGHT TO ME BY CLERK DWIGHT CARTER.  WEARING PROTECTIVE CLOTHING AND GLOVES, I INSPECTED THE PACKAGE TO FIND A CRACK IN THE PLASTIC JAR.  MOST OF THE LIQUID HAD ESCAPED, BUT WHAT REMAINED, I SOLIDIFIED WITH SOLUSORB WHICH ALSO REDUCES FLAMMABILITY.  I THEN BAGGED AND OVERBOXED THE MIXTURE AND THE PLASTIC JAR AND DISPOSED OF IT IN THE PROPER DUMPSTER, ACCORDING TO THE PROPER DISPOSAL METHODS.  THE LOADER SHOULD BE CONTACTED IN THE ORIGIN HUB TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS AND PREVENT ANYMORE CRUSHED PARCELS.

BULK INTERMODAL DISTRIBUTION SERVICES (BIDS) WAS LOADING THIS RAILCAR FROM HIGHWAY CARGO TANK WHEN HOSE BEGAN TO BUCK INDICATING TRANSFER WAS COMPLETE.  BUCKING ACTION OF HOSE CAUSED TOP HOSE SECUREMENT TO BECOME DISCONNECTED AND OUTLET OF HOSE EXITED FILL HOLE, SPRAYING MIST ONTO SURROUNDING AREA,.  CSXT TRACK FORCES WERE WORKING NEARBY AND ONE (1) INDIVIDUAL WAS AFFECTED BY THE MIST.  THIS INDIVIDUAL (DANNY GIBSON) WAS SHOWERED, TAKEN TO UNIV. OF TENN. MEDICAL CENTER, TREATED AND RELEASED. CONTACTS: BIDS MGR JERRY THORTON 615/523-1392.

column168: HOLTRACHEM TRAILER #51-1984 FRUE. TANK TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH APPROXIMATELY 3700 GALLONS OF UN1824 SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION.  THE TRAILER WAS PARKED LOADED WITH LANDING GEAR IN PLACE--LANDING GEAR WAS RESTING ON A STEEL PLATE.  APPROXIMATELY 1/2 HOUR AFTER THE HOLTRACHEM DRIVER LEFT THE TERMINAL WITH ANOTHER LOAD ON ANOTHER TRAILER, TRAILER #51 SLOWLY HEALED OVER ON ITS DRIVER SIDE WITH ONE LEG BENT (HEAVY DUTY LANDING GEAR AND SAND SHOES).  NO PRODUCT LEAK OCURRED AT THIS TIME AND NOT FOR AT LEAST 2 HOURS AFTERWRDS. HOLTRACHEM LEASES THE PARKING AREA FROM SOCAL TRANSPORT, WILMINGTON, CA AN ICC REGULATED TANK CARRIER AND THEY ALSO PARK THEIR TANK TRAILERS ON SITE. SOCAL VOLUNTEERED TO DISCHARGE THE CARGO INTO THEIR TRAILER AND UPRIGHT T51. AFTER DISCHARGING FOR 2 HOURS, WITH SOCAL PERSONNEL AND SUPERVISION, AN AUDIBLE BANG WAS HEARD AND DISCHARGE OCCURRED AND THE MAN HOLE WAS NOW WIDE OPEN.  THE FATALLY INJURED PARTY WAS FOUND APPROXIMATELY 10 MINUTES LATER LAYING UNDER THE FLATBED TRAILER.  THE TWO (2) INJURED PARTIES WERE ATTEMPTING TO PERFORM FIRST AID ON THE VICTIM AND GOT SODIUM HYDROXIDE ON THEIR FACE, HANDS, BACK AND LEGS; BOTH WERE TREATED AND RELEASED THE SAME DAY.  THE OTHER TWO INJURED PARTIES WERE ALSO SPLASHED WHILE RENDERING ASSISTANCE BUT REACHED WATER QUICKLY AND DID NOT REQUIRE MEDICAL ASSISTANCE. NOTIFIED BY PHONE FRIDAY, MAY 29, 1992 WERE THE FOLLOWING: 1. NATIONAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY BOARD BOB CHIPKEVICH/202-382-6585 2. EPA--CAMERON MCDONALD/415-744-2000 3. NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER MR. BRUEYER/1-800-424-8802/REPORT #118853 4. OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES RANDY CLEMENT/1-800-852-7550/REPORT #234;87 5. LA FIRE DEPARTMENT--CAPTAIN NELSON/310-548-7548 AT THIS WRITING, CALOSHA IS INVESTIGATING THE ACCIDENT SITE, CLEAN UP WAS STARTED IMMEDIATELY--FRIDAY PM OF DAY OF ACCIDENT UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF MR.
